Boil a #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the noodles. Once boiling cook the @egg noodle nests{2} for around ~{4%minutes} or until soft enough to eat. Drain the noodles then place them back in a pot of cold water until they are needed.

> Tip: The cold water will stop them from cooking further.

Mix together the @peanut butter{3%tbsp}, @soy sauce{1.5%tbsp} and @sweet chilli sauce{1.5%tbsp}. Add a few tbsp of the boiling noodle water until you have the consistency of runny honey.

Peel the skin from the @ginger{1%thumb} using the edge of a #spoon{}, then finely chop. Take the core out of the @red pepper{1} and slice it into ½cm matchsticks (thinner if possible!). Chop the base from the @pak choi{1} then very thinly slice it widthways. Chop the very bottom from the @spring onions{2} and slice into discs, separating the white and green parts.

Heat @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{} or #wok{}. Once almost smoking hot add in the ginger and the whites of the spring onions. After ~{30%seconds} add in the red pepper and the @sugar snap peas{1}. After ~{2%minutes} add in the pak choi and continue to cook for ~{2%minutes} more.

Drain the noodles and add them to the #pan{} of vegetables. Toss (or stir) the ingredients together for ~{1%minute}. Make some space in the pan and add in the satay sauce. Once it bubbles, mix it into the noodles and vegetables.

Tear up the @Thai holy basil{½%cup} and toss this into the noodles.

Lightly crush and sprinkle over the @dry roasted peanuts{1%tbsp}. Garnish with a sprinkle of the green spring onion and whisper a little prayer to the gods of Thai cooking.